node.text:
For the smoked pork rib tips at My Father’s Barbeque (@myfathersbbq), pitmaster Shalamar Lane (@chefshalamarlane) uses a traditional paprika and cumin spice rub, used by her Alabama-native father, that includes cracked black pepper and coarse salt often found in her mother’s Texas-style barbecue dishes. With a marriage of styles and techniques from both regions, but being served in California, chef Lane carries on her family traditions while also forging something entirely new.

Producer/Director: @Connorreidgram // Camera: @Connorreidgram, @Mur_F // Editor: @mike.imhoff

node.title: How Pitmaster Shalamar Lane Uses Family Traditions at My Father’s Barbeque

node.text:
Torre Lupara’s buffalo mozzarella is about an Italian as a product as you can get. The cheese is classified as DOP Mozzarella di Bufala, meaning everything from the feed the buffalo eat, to the buffalo themselves, to the swirled and stretched mozzarella is grown, housed, and made in a “Denominazione di Origine Protetta”, or Protected Designation of Origin, in Campania, Italy.

Producer/Editor: @carla_francescutti 
Director: @annamuckerman 
Field Producers/Camera: @annamuckerman, Mohamad Ahmed

node.title: How an Italian Dairy Farm Makes 11,000 Pounds of Mozzarella a Day

node.text:
Bangkok-based chefs Chudaree Tam Debhakam (@tamchudaree) and Prin Polsuk (@prinpolsuk) fish for giant river prawns in Thailand’s Sam Khok district to make kanom jeen nam ya — a noodle and curry dish chef Polsuk uncovered from an ancient text. They fashion a makeshift grill rack out of bamboo, and cook the prawns over an open flame right outside in the forest.  

Created & Directed by Paul Travis (@lannafilms) // Producers: Fern Sripungwiwat (@feasttheculture), @Carla_Francescutti, @mcgraw_wolfman //  
Production Consultant: Poonperm Paitayawat // Camera: Tin Guyson (@@tin_guyson), Kingkan Siripiriyakul (@mighty.meng) // Second Camera/Local Editor: Michael Towers  (@bangkokphotographer) // Translation & Content: Miki Thabbanthon (@miki_jung11) // Editors: @carla_francescutti, @mike.imhoff

Host Daniel Geneen (‪@danielgeneen‬) wades deep into the mud of  Frugé Aquafarms’s (@frugeseafood) rice crops. But he’s not harvesting grains — he’s learning how to gather crawfish. The Louisiana farmers discuss how the two crops are  synced, and teach Daniel how to harvest and prepare crawfish for a classic Southern seafood boil.

Host: Daniel Geneen // Producer/Director: @Connorreidgram // Camera: @Connorreidgram, Matthew Koesy (@koesting_along_) // Editor: @mike.imhoff

node.title: How Frugé Aquafarms Produces Over One Million Pounds of Crawfish Each Year

Anyone who’s ever watched a banana go from perfectly ripe to banana-bread-ready-brown in a matter of hours knows how precarious the lifespan of the fruit can be. That’s why those at Top Banana — the largest vendors of Dole bananas in the Northeast — have developed a complex, high-tech system for ripening millions of bananas from all over the world to perfection each week. 🍌

Producer/Director/Editor: @connorreidgram // Camera: @carla_francescutti, @connorreidgram

node.title: How Top Banana Moves Over One Million Pounds of Bananas per Week

“The fear of failure is not present in our universe,” says chef and co-owner Chintan Pandya (@chefchintan) of Dhamaka (@dhamakanyc), one of NYC’s most exciting new restaurants. NYC pop-up Dame (@dame_nyc) was supposed to sell fish and chips for a few weeks in the summer of 2020 during the pandemic. A year later, owners and Eater New Guard 2021 members Ed Szymanski (@ed.z.szymanski) and Patricia Howard (@patricia__howard) are still dunking hunks of hake into the deep fryer. We followed the duo as they tested out recipes six weeks before opening the doors to their permanent space in NYC’s West Village after an explosive response to their crispy battered fish.

Director/Producer: @pelin_liu // Camera: @carla_francescutti, @connorreidgram // Editor: Lucy Morales (@del_fuego)

“The biggest misconception about soul food is that it is unhealthy, not good for you, and that it’s garbage, that it’s trash. It’s just not true,” says chef Deborah VanTrece (@chefdeborahvantrece), as she washes an enormous pile of collard greens. These leafy greens are destined for a tortellini dish with a soul food-spin — combining the traditions and ingredients used by Black chefs in the South, with global cuisines — something that VanTrece is known for at her restaurant Twisted Soul Cookhouse & Pours (@twistedsoulcookhouse) in Atlanta, Georgia. 

Producers: @pelin_liu, @meghanmccarron // Director: @pelin_liu // Camera:  @tjahedo, @laura_ayme_palacio // Editor: Scott Kan

node.title: Chef Deborah VanTrece Honors Soul Food’s History at Her Atlanta Restaurant

At dairy farm La Ferme du Champ Secret (@Fermeduchampsecret) in Normandy, France, owner Patrick Mercier is delighted by the fact that his soft, spreadable Camembert cheese has been said to have “the flavor of the barn.” That’s because this farm is one of only two remaining producers of organic, grass-fed Camembert cheese using traditional methods which “convey the ambiance of the herd” in the cheese.

Producer: @pelin_liu Field // Producer/Director: @annamuckerman // Camera: @annamuckerman, Mohamed Ahmed

node.title: How French Camembert Cheese Is Made at La Ferme Du Champ Secret

Many of NYC’s Michelin-starred restaurants turn to one vendor for their tuna supply: Yama Seafood (@yamaseafood). Director Nobu Yamanashi follows the principles his father, Kingo Yamanashi, set when he started the business over 40 years ago: Never steal or cheat, and always say good morning when you come to work. Now, Yama Seafood specializes in albacore, bigeye, yellow fin, and whopping 400-500 pound bluefin tuna, all supplied to restaurants through the city

Director: @McGraw_wolfman // Producers/Camera: @McGraw_wolfman, @connorreidgram // Editor: @mike.imhoff

For the smoked pork rib tips at My Father’s Barbeque (@myfathersbbq), pitmaster Shalamar Lane (@chefshalamarlane) uses a traditional paprika and cumin spice rub, used by her Alabama-native father, that includes cracked black pepper and coarse salt often found in her mother’s Texas-style barbecue dishes. With a marriage of styles and techniques from both regions, but being served in California, chef Lane carries on her family traditions while also forging something entirely new.

Producer/Director: @Connorreidgram // Camera: @Connorreidgram, @Mur_F // Editor: @mike.imhoff

node.text:
Southern California has steadily emerged as one of America’s best barbecue regions, and Los Angeles is its capital. This is Barbecue Week on @eater_la, and it's all about the city's finest smoked meats. 

In a place as diverse as Los Angeles, that means zigzagging from Texas-style stars to smoky brisket with a side of cornbread bibingka at a Filipino barbecue mainstay, to pit-roasted goat barbacoa, to char siu ribs served out of a garage. 

Tap our profile link or head to @eater_la for all the Barbecue Week stories. 

📸 Eater LA photographer @wonhophoto at @zef_hawaiian

node.text:
Mac and cheese ice cream kind of broke the internet two weeks ago. Posts about the Van Leeuwen/Kraft collab were besieged with comments of disgust, shock, and outrage. Civil wars erupted in group chats. “This Is What Greets You at the Gates of Hell” declared @thecut of the cheese-flavored pint (which actually turned out to taste very good)
 
But the particular revulsion this flavor inspired was a little strange considering just how much we all actually love cheese-based desserts. Cheesecake comes to mind. So do crispy-topped kanafeh slices, crunchy and creamy cannoli, cardamom-flavored ras malai, cheddar-tinged apple pies, ricotta-filled cakes, and many more. As @hidayna puts it: “Cheese shows up in dozens of desserts and cultures, and that’s because rich, cheesy things taste good when they’re made a little sweeter.”
 
The particular pints that kicked off this discourse sold out, but they aren’t the only way to get mac and cheese ice cream; it’s a very simple flavor to create at home, given all the magic is in your ice cream base (simple) and your powdered cheese packet fished from a box of elbow macaroni (simpler). 
 
In our profile link, find Dayna’s recipe for both a Kraft mac and cheese-flavored ice cream and a herbed white cheddar ice cream made with perennial pantry favorite Annie’s.
